O God! Thou art my God alone;  
From dawn’s pale hush to midnight’s deep,  
My spirit knows Thy voice, Thy tone,  
That calls me forth from restless sleep.  

No distant star, no ancient stone,  
Could claim the longing in my breast;  
For in Thy gaze I am full known,  
And by Thy grace, my soul is blessed.  

Mountains may crumble, rivers roam;  
The world may change and kingdoms fall;  
Yet, anchored firm, my love hath grown—  
O God! My God, my all in all.

Go, go, my naughty girl, and kiss
the thunder from the restless sky;
let wildness tremble on your lips
as secrets in the meadow fly.
Barehearted, claim the stormy night,
dance with the foxes in the rain;
let every rule be set alight,
then skip away from every chain.
Go, go, and let your laughter spin
a tangled web of dreams and dare;
for in each kiss, a world begins—
and mischief lingers everywhere.
